{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f3c61d93-a962-43de-80b2-67c4a1ac21f5","content":"The project directory doesn't exist yet. No worries — here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool to NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet package metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n\n  <!-- Must be Exe for stdio transport -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n</PropertyGroup>\n\n<!-- Include a README in the package -->\n<ItemGroup>\n  <None Include=\"README.md\" Pack=\"true\" PackagePath=\"/\" />\n</ItemGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — this is the critical property that makes it installable via `dotnet tool install`.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run (defaults to assembly name if omitted).\n3. **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — required for both stdio transport and dotnet tools.\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```\n\nWould you like me to update your actual `.csproj` file with these properties?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"394c58c4-f5c5-4866-88dd-5b9be86f859d","outputTokens":514,"requestId":"158A:301230:31918E8:3647C2A:69FBE674"},"id":"1c388d70-bad2-4479-b161-063482daa5e9","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:10:23.598Z","parentId":"d52eedd5-a0cb-487b-894e-466db1cdb8cb"}
